<subSubSection id="E4C4FE2F09926743F454301BD8A07234" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="typification">
<paragraph id="23EEF8C6E0A5240B876EDF280FA2550E" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Typification.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="6F4B244F14E2A1BA73B882C7C133BA0F" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
The holotype of 
<taxonomicName id="CF647CA03F0D0AB23579C57611CD81D1" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Ipomoea" kingdom="Plantae" order="Solanales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="federalis">
<emphasis id="C5C81C625C68F91EF821F5D363B80E68" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Ipomoea federalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
at S is a small fragment, so we have designated the isotype at UB as an epitype as this species can only be adequately interpreted through this second specimen. The synonymy of this species has been discussed extensively by Austin and Bianchini (1998).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="E55A1A75622A0616C422F7B60672DB9C" pageId="0" pageNumber="1" type="notes">
<paragraph id="3BF7717075A527FDBFEC4538693A1A31" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Note.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="22C45482865C313340048AAFBD609C49" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">
Very distinct because of the inflorescence of bracteolate heads, the strongly veined bracteoles forming an involucre around the flowers. However it is quite variable with bracteoles not always as well developed, so sometimes merely lanceolate, and the corolla sometimes up to 5.5 cm as in 
<emphasis id="6BA21F0F683E7357C4EFA19366A166EA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="1">Marin</emphasis>
2112, which is exceptionally robust.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
